# **Project Proposal: G11 \- Microservice based CMS Platform**

# **Background / Problem Statement**

Traditional CMS platforms are often monolithic, restricted, with limited scaling. Furthermore SaaS solutions often lock you out of control. To solve these issues we are building a FOSS **Kubernetes microservice CMS with automated CI/CD, zero-trust, and observability**, **taking the best of cloud-native architecture** and applying it to content management.

# **Success Objectives**

* **Automation**: Reliably automate deployment and system maintenance to reduce human effort needed to manage systems.  
* **Scalability:** Keep horizontal scalability in mind when designing and implementing system  
* **Observability**: Allow observability into system functionality to detect problems and track performance  
* **Ease of Use:** System be well documented, easy to set-up, maintain and modify  
* **Security:** Ensure security best practices are followed in planning and implementation to ensure information security

# **Scope & High-level tools**

## In-Scope

**Version Control:** Git will be used along with GitHub to collaborate and share the codebase  
**Containerization & Orchestralization:** Applications will be containerized with Open Container Initiative(OCI) standards using docker to allow scalability and orchestrated through Kubernetes (k8s).  
**Microservice based architecture:** Microservices will be used to help with scalability and development management.  
**Automatic load-based scaling:** Ensure pod scaling within the cluster based on load using a pod scaler such as Horizontal Pod Autoscaling  
**CI/CD:** An integration and deployment pipeline will be automated through GitHub Actions  
**Monitoring and Observability:** Log monitoring with the Openserach stack and metric monitoring with Graffana-Pormetheus, with alerting for failures  
**Infrastructure as Code (IaC):** Terraform will be used for provisioning and managing infrastructure  
**Sysadmin automation:** Use ansible to automate system administration tasks  
Automated   
**Security Scanning:** Trivy and grype can be used to do automated scanning of the container images and code base  
**Automatic Deployment:** AgroCD in combination with helm can be used to automate kubernetes deployment  
**Smoke tests:** testing can be done to do smoke tests  
**Canary deployment and rollback strategy:** Argo Rollouts can be used to handle canary based rollouts to production and rollback in case of failure metrics  
**Cloud Agnostic system:** Ensure cloud agnosticism by not using managed services such as RDS, EKS, Cloudwatch  
**Zero-Trust security:** Proper zero trust principles in architecture, properly manage secrets, use mTLS in orchestration via a service mesh such as isitio, deny all permissions by default  
**Identity & Access Management:** Use WSO2 Asgardeo as the IAM server to provide secure authentication, authorization, and federated identity management across microservices.  
**Documentation:** Ensure documentation is created and maintained on setting-up, deploying, maintaining the system

## Optionally in-scope

**Backup/recovery:** Ensure backup and recovery policies are in place and tested  
**SAST/Dependency checks:** Use tools to do static code testing in the CI pipeline  
**Private artefact registry:** Use a private docker registry deployed with Kubernetes  
**Dynamic Infrastructure Inventory:** Terraform → generate Ansible inventory → auto-configure nodes.  
**K8s node scaling:** Investigate using a tool such as karpenter to automatically scale compute for the cluster (node scaling)  
**API Security & Management:** Use WSO2 API Manager (APIM) as the centralized API gateway for enforcing authentication, throttling, rate limiting, analytics, and secure exposure of internal APIs.

## Out of scope

**UI/UX design, code based performance optimizations, complete feature set:** These things can be optimised in V2, focus of the MVP is the devOps practices and architecture.  
**Complete cell based architecture:** No capacity or need for this due to limited functionality

# **Proposed Solution**

## Application features

The application will be a CMS platform that provides users functionality to maintain and publish content to a blog site. The following user roles will be available: author, editor, admin, reader. Observability tools will be used independently to show infrastructure usage and alert for failures

## Microservice architecture

The application will be broken down into 5 microservices: User Service, Content Service, Media Service, Category & Tag Service and the Comment Service. These microservices will be used by the frontend to give functionality.

## Deployment Environment

The deployment environment would be on AWS. There will be separate staging and production environments.

## CI/CD Pipeline

GitHub actions will be used the pipeline will have the following steps:Build & Containerize,Security & Compliance Scans, Deploy to Staging, Manual Approval for Production, Production Deployment

# **Risks & Mitigation**

| Risk | Level | Mitigation |
| :---- | :---- | :---- |
| GitHub actions minutes run out | HIGH | Move repositories to other orgs/pay for additional minutes |
| Run out of AWS credit for a month | HIGH | Do calculations for the resources before deploying. Add a nuke button. Always monitor the credit limit, add alarms for 400 USD. Bring down unused resources. |
| Unable to complete all coding features in time | MID | Prioritize the essential microservices and features first |
| Unable to have full scale staging and production | MID | Make staging a smaller scale if needed |
| Team member becomes unavailable due to unforeseen circumstances | MID | Have 2 team members always aware on each task, make sure commits are done daily to ensure work is synced up |

# **Expected Outcomes / Benefits**

* *Project success will be measured by delivering a secure, observable, automated, and scalable CMS platform that demonstrates the practical implementation of DevOps best practices in a real-world, production-grade system.*  
* A fully functional, cloud-agnostic CMS platform deployed using microservices and Kubernetes, demonstrating the application of modern DevOps and Zero-Trust principles. Including:  
  CI/CD pipeline using GitHub Actions, Helm, and ArgoCD, capable of continuously building, testing, scanning, and deploying code with minimal manual intervention.  
* Improved scalability and reliability through load-based pod scaling, ensuring the platform can automatically handle varying workloads.  
* Enhanced observability and monitoring, achieved through Prometheus, Grafana, and the OpenSearch Stack, allowing real-time visibility into system health, performance, and logs.  
* Secure system design following Zero-Trust architecture, including mTLS enforcement, secret management, and identity-based access control via an IAM solution such as Asgardeo.  
* Reduced operational overhead by automating infrastructure provisioning (Terraform) and configuration management (Ansible).  
* Efficient and repeatable deployments through Infrastructure-as-Code and containerization standards (Docker \+ OCI).  
* Resilient release process with canary deployments and automated rollback mechanisms for failure recovery.  
* Comprehensive documentation covering deployment, maintenance, and troubleshooting procedures, making the system easy to understand and extend.
